summary: Tenth Doctor Audio Adventures: “No Place“
title: Tenth Doctor Audio Adventures: “No Place“
body:
The sheer and utter awkwardness of The Doctor and Donna trying to pretend they’re a couple is a bit cringey (because of their brother/sister dynamic) but also hilarious. I just kept picturing

and then after the nose “booping” bit, all I could think of was the Bill Murry and Carol Kane scene in Scrooged and couldn’t stop laughing.

They definitely wouldn’t have been able to do a story like that with The Doctor and Rose cause they wouldn’t have been able to keep their hands to themselves. The audio track would have been nothing but giggling and kissing noises:

“Excuse me Dr. Smith but we’re trying to conduct an interview. Could you and your wife stop making out for like five minutes?”

Meanwhile Jackie’s in the background muttering “Not shaggin’ my arse.”

Anyways, it was a bit creepy in parts as well but overall a great DW story. Plus Wilf is Awesome. Even if he doesn’t know to take the marshmallows out of the bag before toasting them.

Up Next: One Mile Down

caption:
“One belongs to New York instantly, one belongs to it as much in five minutes as in five years.”

                                                                             — Tom Wolfe

Founded in 1624, New York City has become a point of pride for America as the home to the Statue of Liberty, Empire State Building, Broadway, and more. People come from all over the globe for its people and its attractions. But for most, it’s a place for dreams; for new beginnings; for endless possibilities; for the start of a new life. New York City holds a different and indistinct meaning for everybody. What will it mean to you?

Bright Lights Big City is an appless, OC roleplay set in the five boroughs of New York City. Our doors opened in July of 2016 and have become the home of dozens of members and nearly 100 characters. We’re looking for active, dedicated writers to join our group and find their home with us in the city the never sleeps.

summary: Good Omens Review: The Summer's Best New Show
title: Good Omens Review: The Summer's Best New Show
excerpt: Amazon's Good Omens miniseries finally enters the pop-culture consciousness later this month, [...]
description: The characters on Good Omens feel incredibly lived-in, even when they have the most whimsical qualities. Tennant and Sheen, in particular, are absolutely exceptional, both individually and as a duo. Tennant’s Crowley brings together the intimidating swagger of Kilgrave and the likable eccentricities of the Tenth Doctor, but in a way that feels entirely new and fun. As Aziraphale, Sheen brings so much nuance to a seemingly goody-two-shoes character, with hilarious and emotionally resonant results. Together, the pair of fan-favorite actors create a relationship that’s electrifying to watch, with banter that plays out like the best possible version of The Odd Couple. At the core of it all, you can clearly feel how much the unlikely friends care for each other, and it’s that emotion that will make audiences want to follow the pair anywhere and everywhere.
